      "SummaryText": "Executive Summary\r\nJX Nippon Chemical Texas Inc.; 10500 Bay Area Blvd.; Pasadena, Texas 77507 \r\n1 - ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION AND EMERGENCY RESPONSE POLICIES\r\nJX Nippon Chemical Texas Inc. (JX NCTI) is committed to operating and maintaining all of its processes (especially those using hazardous substances) in a safe and responsible manner. JX NCTI uses a combination of accidental release prevention programs and emergency response planning programs to help ensure the safety of its employees and the public, as well as protection of the environment. This document provides a brief overview of the comprehensive risk management activities that JX NCTI has designed and implemented, including:\r\n\u00bf\tA description of our facility and the storage and transfer of substances regulated by EPA RMP.\r\n\u00bf\tAn overview of our accidental release prevention programs\r\n\u00bf\tA five-year accident history for accidental releases of chemicals regulated by EPA's RMP\r\n\u00bf\tAn overview of the emergency response program\r\n\u00bf\tAn overview of planned improvements at the facility to help prevent accidental chemical releases from occurring and adversely affecting employees, the public, or the environment\r\n2 - STATIONARY SOURCE AND REGULATED SUBSTANCES\r\nJX NCTI is a chemical manufacturing facility located in Harris County, Texas. The plant consists of reactors, distillation columns, storage tanks and shipping and receiving facilities for bulk tank trucks as well as rail cars. JX NCTI primarily manufactures chemicals used in the carbonless copy paper, electrical capacitors, heat transfer fluids, and EPDM rubber industries. Some by-products are produced and are sold as fuels and solvents.\r\nThe majority of the chemicals handled at JX NCTI are non-hazardous. However, JX NCTI does have three regulated flammable chemicals under the Risk Management Program. These three chemicals are 1,3 Butadiene (BD), Propylene, and Isobutylene. JX NCTI does not store or process any of the listed toxic chemicals.\r\nThese chemicals ha"
    },
    {
      "ESSeqNum": 2,
      "FacilityID": 1000069905,
      "SummaryText": "Transfer compressor systems have automatic shutdowns on high temperature, high level and high or low pressure.\r\n11.\tSeal less canned pumps are used to eliminate leakage due to seal failures.\r\n12.\tRemote actuated valves to isolate and limit a release installed on 1,3 Butadiene storage tank.\r\n13.\tPlant wide modern Fire Water System\r\n14.\tJX NCTI maintains a fully staffed and highly trained emergency response team.\r\n15.\tJX NCTI is a member of Channel Industries Mutual Aid (CIMA), which is an agreement with other industrial neighbors to provide assistance in emergency response efforts.\r\n16.\tA rigorous Mechanical Integrity program that covers process equipment and piping.\r\nThese individual elements of JX NCTI's prevention program work together to prevent accidental chemical releases. \r\n4 - FIVE-YEAR ACCIDENT HISTORY\r\nJX NCTI maintains records for all significant accidental chemical releases that occur at its facility. There have been no RMP accidents in the past five years.\r\n5 - EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROGRAM\r\nJX NCTI maintains an emergency response and contingency plan, which consolidates all of the various federal, state, and local regulatory requirements for emergency response planning. This program provides the essential planning and training for effectively protecting workers, the public, and the environment during emergency situations. Furthermore, JX NCTI is a member of a Local Emergency Planning Committee, and the CIMA organization. Elements of our emergency response plan that reduce the impact on the defined receptors include: Fire protection equipment, water curtain capabilities to minimize releases, alarm systems, trained responders, community alert system, and communication links to offsite responders.\r\n6 - PLANNED CHANGES TO IMPROVE SAFETY\r\nThe safety and environmental training program have been updated and improved and continues to improve. The Behavioral Based Safety Program has been revised, and observations submitted by all employees are continuously reviewe"
    },
