      "SummaryText": "ve been identified to have the potential to cause offsite consequences in the event of a substantial release. Offsite consequences were determined assuming maximum possible inventory even though the inventory of these chemicals is often reduced.\r\nJX NCTI's accidental release prevention programs and contingency planning efforts help effectively manage the hazards that are posed to employees, the public, and the environment in the storage, transfer, and processing of these chemicals.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n3 - GENERAL ACCIDENTAL RELEASE PREVENTION PROGRAM AND CHEMICAL-SPECIFIC PREVENTION STEPS\r\nJX NCTI takes a systematic, proactive approach to preventing accidental releases of hazardous chemicals. JX NCTI's management systems address each of the key features of successful prevention programs including: Process safety information, process hazard analysis, operating procedures, training, mechanical integrity, management of change, pre-startup safety review, compliance audits, incident investigation, employee participation, hot work permit procedure, emergency planning and response, and contractor safety.\r\nAs part of JX NCTI's prevention efforts, it has implemented the following chemical-specific prevention steps:\r\n1.\tPressurized tanks are equipped with a pressure relief device routed to a control device.\r\n2.\tStorage tanks are equipped with pressure, temperature and level instrumentation.\r\n3.\tDigital Control Systems (DCS) alarms linked to instrumentation are programmed for specific conditions. \r\n4.\tKey parameters are continuously monitored in a central control room by highly trained DCS operators.\r\n5.\tSystems are pressure and leak tested before chemicals are introduced.\r\n6.\tTanks are built and installed per ASME and NFPA Codes.\r\n7.\tAutomatic safety interlocks or emergency shutdowns are programmed into the DCS.\r\n8.\tArea leak detectors are installed and monitored by DCS operators.\r\n9.\tStorage tanks for BD and Propylene have fireproof insulation for passive protection in a fire event.\r\n10."
